
### 1) Aaron

- Location: Waterfall
- Quick summary: Muscular enemy that flexes; attacks with winks and flexing motions creating heart projectiles.
- Attacks / Behavior: Spawns pink heart bullets in simple patterns; slow-moving but can fill the box if not careful.
- ACT / Spare: Flex back at Aaron to make him uncomfortable and spare. Can also spare via Talk/Compliment.
- Implementation notes: Simple heart-projectile spawner with radial or grid patterns. Low HP enemy. Track "flex" ACT to set spare flag.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Aaron

---

### 2) Asgore Dreemurr

- Location: New Home (boss)
- Quick summary: Final boss in Neutral/Pacifist routes; uses trident attacks and fire magic with multiple phases.
- Attacks / Behavior: Trident sweeps (horizontal/vertical), fireball volleys, and wave-based fire patterns. Multi-phase with increasing intensity.
- ACT / Spare: Story-driven; Mercy option becomes available after specific dialog/item interactions. Fight scripted for narrative resolution.
- Implementation notes: Multi-phase boss with telegraphed trident attacks and fire spawners. Include cutscene hooks and item interaction (Butterscotch Pie effect).
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Asgore_Dreemurr/In_Battle

---

### 3) Asriel Dreemurr

- Location: True Pacifist finale
- Quick summary: Ultimate boss with extreme bullet-hell patterns, soul mechanics, and multiple phases with cutscene integration.
- Attacks / Behavior: Dense projectile volleys, rotating hazards, soul-color changes, and scripted attack sequences tied to narrative beats.
- ACT / Spare: Non-standard spare; resolved via specific story choices and SAVE actions during the fight.
- Implementation notes: High-complexity multi-phase system with rapid pattern switches. Heavy use of cutscene triggers and special mechanics.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Asriel_Dreemurr/In_Battle

---

### 4) Astigmatism

- Location: CORE / Hard Mode
- Quick summary: Eye enemy with rotating laser beams and burst projectiles.
- Attacks / Behavior: Rotating thin beams that sweep the box; short bursts of fast straight-line projectiles requiring lateral dodging.
- ACT / Spare: Standard HP-based defeat/spare. Dialog ACTs available but not required.
- Implementation notes: Rotating ray emitters with configurable speed; burst spawners for secondary attacks. Hard Mode scaling supported.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Astigmatism

---

### 5) Chilldrake

- Location: Snowdin (replaces Snowdrake if Snowdrake is killed)
- Quick summary: Drake enemy with ice shard attacks; opposite dialog mechanics to Snowdrake.
- Attacks / Behavior: Crescent ice shards in parabolic arcs and straight lines. Similar attack patterns to Snowdrake.
- ACT / Spare: "Agree" with Chilldrake during dialog prompts to pacify (opposite of Snowdrake's laugh mechanic).
- Implementation notes: Reuse Snowdrake's projectile systems. Track dialog state and spare on "Agree" ACT.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Chilldrake

---

### 6) Dogamy and Dogaressa

- Location: Snowdin (miniboss duo)
- Quick summary: Married dog couple that attack in coordination; behavior changes if one is defeated.
- Attacks / Behavior: Axe drops forming heart shapes, bark rings with blue bullets, coordinated sweeps with safe gaps.
- ACT / Spare: Pet/Roll Around both dogs to spare. Using the Stick item triggers instant spare.
- Implementation notes: Two-actor system with synchronized attacks. Implement partner-loss behavior (surviving partner becomes faster/sadder).
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Dogamy_and_Dogaressa

---

### 7) Doggo

- Location: Snowdin
- Quick summary: Dog sentry that attacks with sword slashes; can only see moving targets.
- Attacks / Behavior: Blue sword slashes requiring player to stand still. Fast horizontal sweeps across the box.
- ACT / Spare: Pet Doggo after standing still during attacks to calm him and spare.
- Implementation notes: Blue-attack mechanic (stand still to avoid). Simple horizontal sweep patterns. Low HP.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Doggo

---

### 8) Dummy

- Location: Ruins (tutorial encounter)
- Quick summary: Training dummy used to teach battle mechanics; minimal threat.
- Attacks / Behavior: Cotton projectiles that move slowly or stay stationary; designed to be easily avoided.
- ACT / Spare: Talk or attack to end encounter. Sparing immediately also works. Tutorial-focused design.
- Implementation notes: Slow or static projectiles. Use as early tutorial with clear safe zones and long reaction windows.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Dummy

---

### 9) Endogeny

- Location: True Laboratory (Amalgamate)
- Quick summary: Dog amalgamate with erratic multi-headed attacks and unpredictable patterns.
- Attacks / Behavior: Radial bursts from multiple heads, bouncing dog heads, and overlapping projectile waves.
- ACT / Spare: Pet/Beckon/Play repeatedly to calm all heads and spare. Each head has separate state.
- Implementation notes: Multiple emitter points with offset timings. Track per-head state for ACT interactions.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Endogeny

---

### 10) Final Froggit

- Location: CORE
- Quick summary: Evolved Froggit with homing flies and aggressive patterns.
- Attacks / Behavior: Homing fly projectiles that pause then track player; large jump attacks that cross the arena.
- ACT / Spare: Mystify or Compliment to weaken/spare. Standard HP reduction also works.
- Implementation notes: Implement homing projectiles with delayed tracking. Jump hazard moves across box with collision zone.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Final_Froggit

---

### 11) Flowey (Photoshop Flowey / Omega Flowey)

- Location: Neutral route finale
- Quick summary: Transformed Flowey boss with extreme bullet-hell and phase-based attacks. Multiple forms.
- Attacks / Behavior: Dense bullet clusters, rotating hazards, scripted minigames, and phase transitions. Uses "soul capture" mechanics.
- ACT / Spare: Story-scripted resolution via calling for help and soul intervention. Not a standard spare.
- Implementation notes: Large-scale pattern system with heavy pooling. Phase transitions and external soul-based mechanics.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Flowey

---

### 12) Froggit

- Location: Ruins
- Quick summary: Common early enemy; flies spawn and simple jump pattern.
- Attacks / Behavior: Small flies that travel in downward arcs; occasional jump that repositions Froggit and spawns more flies.
- ACT / Spare: Compliment to spare quickly. Low HP allows easy defeat.
- Implementation notes: Arc-moving projectiles with sine-wave paths. Simple state machine: idle → attack → pause.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Froggit

---

### 13) Glyde

- Location: Snowdin (secret optional boss)
- Quick summary: Wealthy character with star projectiles and timed donation mechanic.
- Attacks / Behavior: Star-shaped projectiles in waves; some explode into smaller stars. Occasional no-attack turns.
- ACT / Spare: Pay/Applaud sequence (Applaud twice, then do Nothing or pay) to spare.
- Implementation notes: Star spawners with explosion child projectiles. Low-probability no-op attack for variety.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Glyde

---

### 14) Greater Dog

- Location: Snowdin (boss)
- Quick summary: Giant armored dog with spear attacks and pose-based patterns.
- Attacks / Behavior: Spear/lance attacks depend on dog's pose. Projectiles spawn based on stance (sitting, standing, etc.).
- ACT / Spare: Pet repeatedly to increase excitement and spare. Ignore causes boredom and also leads to spare.
- Implementation notes: Pose-state machine drives attack patterns. Visual pose cues link to projectile spawn logic.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Greater_Dog

---

### 15) Gyftrot

- Location: Snowdin
- Quick summary: Reindeer with junk decorations; gift-themed mechanics.
- Attacks / Behavior: Present boxes that shuffle then rise; snowflakes in waves. Presents may be blue (stand-still) attacks.
- ACT / Spare: Undecorate to remove all junk, then Gift/spare. Decoration count affects dialog.
- Implementation notes: Track decoration list (up to 3 items). Present projectiles with blue-attack flags. Snowflake wave spawners.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Gyftrot

---

### 16) Ice Cap

- Location: Snowdin
- Quick summary: Ice creature with top-hat projectiles and temperature-based dialog.
- Attacks / Behavior: Upward-firing hat projectiles from floor; zig-zag ice waves creating safe corridors.
- ACT / Spare: Ignore twice to make Ice Cap insecure and spare. Stealing the cap changes its form.
- Implementation notes: Floor spawners for upward projectiles; timed zig-zag pattern generators with safe lanes.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Ice_Cap

---

### 17) Jerry

- Location: Snowdin
- Quick summary: Annoying enemy that extends other enemies' attack duration but has no direct attacks.
- Attacks / Behavior: Passive enemy; increases duration of other monsters' attacks by ~2 seconds when present.
- ACT / Spare: Ditch to remove temporarily. Can be spared via group ACTs (if fighting with others).
- Implementation notes: Modifier entity that adds time delays to other actors' attack phases. Ditch = timed removal flag.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Jerry

---

### 18) Knight Knight

- Location: CORE
- Quick summary: Armored knight with dragon pet; sleep and sword-based attacks.
- Attacks / Behavior: Sword sweeps, dragon breath projectiles, and sung lullabies that can put player to sleep (reduces defense).
- ACT / Spare: Sing to put Knight Knight to sleep, making spare possible.
- Implementation notes: Sword sweep hazards and dragon fireball emitters. Sleep status affects player defense. Singing ACT sets spare flag.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Knight_Knight

---

### 19) Lemon Bread

- Location: True Laboratory (Amalgamate)
- Quick summary: Bread amalgamate with face attacks and unsettling dialog.
- Attacks / Behavior: Face projectiles that move erratically; some text-based hazards appear on screen.
- ACT / Spare: Flex, Hum, or Unhug repeatedly to pacify different components and spare.
- Implementation notes: Erratic face projectiles with randomized paths. Multi-component ACT tracking for spare condition.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Lemon_Bread

---

### 20) Lesser Dog

- Location: Snowdin
- Quick summary: Small dog with extendable neck; petting causes neck to grow comically.
- Attacks / Behavior: Bone projectiles and dog-shaped hazards; patterns become sillier as dog is pet more.
- ACT / Spare: Pet repeatedly (neck extends each time) until dog is content and spare becomes available.
- Implementation notes: Pet counter modifies visuals and attack patterns. Bone spawners with silly trajectories at high pet counts.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Lesser_Dog

---

### 21) Loox

- Location: Ruins
- Quick summary: Eyeball enemy with bouncing orbs and wiggle-trail attacks.
- Attacks / Behavior: Large orbs that bounce off walls/floor with acceleration; segmented bullet trails that move horizontally with sine wave.
- ACT / Spare: "Don't Pick On" or "Pick On" produce different dialog but both can lead to spare with low HP.
- Implementation notes: Bounce physics (velocity inversion on boundaries). Sine-offset horizontal trails. Low HP.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Loox

---

### 22) Lost Souls

- Location: True Pacifist (Asriel fight phase)
- Quick summary: Manifestations of main characters' souls; appear as scripted encounters during final battle.
- Attacks / Behavior: Character-specific attack patterns from Toriel, Asgore, Sans, Papyrus, Undyne, Alphys. Each uses simplified versions of their signature attacks.
- ACT / Spare: SAVE each lost soul by using specific ACTs related to their character memories.
- Implementation notes: Scripted encounter sequence with per-character attack sets. SAVE mechanic triggers cutscenes and progression.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Lost_Souls

---

### 23) Mad Dummy

- Location: Waterfall (Garbage Dump)
- Quick summary: Dummy boss that summons dummy clones, rockets, and knife attacks. Can become Glad Dummy in Genocide.
- Attacks / Behavior: Rows of dummy clones sliding horizontally with gaps; homing rockets; white scribble beams; knife throws in final phase.
- ACT / Spare: Cheer three times in Neutral to spare. In Genocide becomes Glad Dummy (instantly spareable).
- Implementation notes: Clone row spawners with gap patterns; brief-homing rockets; scripted knife phase. State switch for Glad Dummy variant.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Mad_Dummy

---

### 24) Mad Mew Mew

- Location: Switch version exclusive encounter
- Quick summary: Mew Mew doll possessed by Mad Dummy's ghost; uses body-swap mechanics and claw attacks.
- Attacks / Behavior: Teleporting slashes, multi-directional claw swipes, heart-shaped bullet patterns. Body parts attack separately in phases.
- ACT / Spare: Console-specific mechanics involving Joy-Con movement. Touch/hug ACTs to spare after defeating phases.
- Implementation notes: Teleport mechanics with telegraphed slashes. Separate hitboxes for body parts. Phase-based progression.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Mad_Mew_Mew

---

### 25) Madjick

- Location: CORE
- Quick summary: Wizard enemy with chaser orbs and corner-spawning hazards.
- Attacks / Behavior: Slow chaser orb that follows player and leaves cross hazards; corner orbs that teleport and fire cross-shaped projectiles.
- ACT / Spare: Stare at orbs to weaken them. Use Clear Mind + Talk, or remain still during chaser. Using Stick also works.
- Implementation notes: Chaser AI with configurable pursuit speed. Corner spawner that relocates based on player position. Cross-pattern emitters.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Madjick

---

### 26) Memoryhead

- Location: True Laboratory (Amalgamate)
- Quick summary: Amalgamate with multiple heads that create memory-based projectile patterns.
- Attacks / Behavior: Rings of small bullets with memory/face symbols. Heads spawn projectiles in coordinated or random patterns.
- ACT / Spare: Refuse/Cell/Flex repeatedly to calm different memory components and spare.
- Implementation notes: Multi-head emitter system with pattern memory. Ring and radial spawn patterns. Track ACT state per component.
- Source: https://undertale.fandom.com/wiki/Memoryhead

